          <section id="what-is-rfid" class="scroll-mt-24">
            <h2 class="text-3xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-5">1. What RFID means and how systems are built</h2>
            <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
              RFID (Radio-Frequency Identification) is a family of technologies that uses radio waves to identify, track, and manage objects without requiring line-of-sight contact or a battery in the tracked item. An RFID system combines three parts &mdash; a tag attached to the object, a reader that interrogates tags via radio, and a host application that interprets tag data as business events (inventory counted, person entered a door, garment circulated through laundry). Unlike barcodes, which require a clear optical view of a printed pattern, RFID reads through packaging, fabric, plastic, and even shallow water, and can inventory hundreds of tagged items simultaneously at distances from a few centimeters (HF / NFC) to over 10 meters (UHF / active tags).
            </p>
            <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
              The technology has commercial roots going back to WWII IFF (Identification Friend or Foe) transponders and matured into modern passive RFID through 1980s-1990s work at Los Alamos, IBM, and NXP predecessor Philips Semiconductors. The 2003 US Department of Defense and Walmart supplier mandates established UHF Gen2 as the supply-chain standard; the NFC Forum's 2004 founding by Nokia, Philips, and Sony crystallized HF RFID as the consumer-facing standard for payments and smart cards. Today, 42 billion passive UHF tags shipped globally in 2024 (RAIN Alliance, 2024), and over 2.4 billion NFC-enabled smartphones are in active use worldwide (NFC Forum, 2025) &mdash; making RFID one of the most ubiquitous invisible technologies in daily operations.
            </p>
            <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
              Three functional RFID categories matter for buyers. <strong>Passive tags</strong> have no battery and harvest power from the reader's electromagnetic field &mdash; this is over 99% of deployed tags, ranging from $0.04 per retail sticker to $3.00 per on-metal industrial tag. <strong>Semi-passive (BAP) tags</strong> carry a small battery to extend read range or support sensor functions (temperature, tilt) but still respond to reader interrogation rather than broadcasting. <strong>Active tags</strong> have their own radio and power source, broadcasting at regular intervals for real-time location systems (RTLS); these cost $15-100 per unit and are used in high-value asset tracking, container shipping, and healthcare equipment fleets. This pillar guide focuses on passive RFID &mdash; which represents over 95% of B2B procurement volume and is the right starting point for virtually all buyers.
            </p>
            <div class="grid lg:grid-cols-[1.05fr_0.95fr] gap-8 items-start">
              <div class="space-y-4 text-gray-600 leading-relaxed">
                <p>
                  RFID stands for Radio Frequency Identification. In practical terms, it means a reader communicates with a tag, card or label using radio waves so an object, person or asset can be identified without manual contact or line-of-sight scanning.
                </p>
                <p>
                  A typical RFID system includes three parts: the credential itself, the reader hardware and the software or operational process that decides what happens after the read event. When one of those pieces is mismatched, the project becomes harder to deploy even if the tag itself is technically correct.
                </p>
                <p>
                  That is why product selection should be based on the full workflow rather than only the chip name or the visible product shape.
                </p>
              </div>
              <div class="rounded-3xl border border-gray-200 bg-gray-50 p-6">
