          <section id="rfp-template" class="scroll-mt-24">
            <h2 class="text-3xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-5">12. RFP template &mdash; what to include when quoting RFID vendors</h2>
            <p class="text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
              Procurement teams evaluating RFID vendors often receive generic brochures rather than quotes they can actually compare. The 14-point RFP template below is what RFIDAK uses internally to make sure buyer inquiries come back with apples-to-apples comparable proposals. Copy this list into your RFP document and send it to 3-5 vendors simultaneously — the responses will separate serious RFID suppliers from marketplace resellers within 48 hours.
            </p>

            <div class="grid gap-5 md:grid-cols-2">
              <div class="rounded-2xl border border-gray-200 bg-gray-50 p-6">
                <p class="eyebrow-label text-[#0d7377] mb-3">Section A &middot; Technical specification (must be precise)</p>
                <ol class="space-y-3 text-sm text-gray-700">
                  <li><strong>1. Frequency band &amp; regional sub-band</strong> &mdash; e.g. "UHF Gen2v2 at FCC 902-928 MHz for US, ETSI 865.6-867.6 MHz for EU" (not "UHF" alone)</li>
                  <li><strong>2. Chip family &amp; model</strong> &mdash; e.g. "NXP UCODE 9" or "Impinj M730" (not "any UHF chip"). List acceptable substitutes if supply shortage.</li>
                  <li><strong>3. Antenna specification</strong> &mdash; size, material, target read range in the ACTUAL mounting condition (on-metal, through plastic, in water, etc.)</li>
                  <li><strong>4. Form factor &amp; dimensions</strong> &mdash; with mechanical drawing or reference sample, not prose description</li>
                  <li><strong>5. Encoding requirement</strong> &mdash; EPC / UID scheme, TID requirement, lock bit state, encoding verification method</li>
                  <li><strong>6. Printing / personalization</strong> &mdash; CMYK front + back, laser engraving, silkscreen, thermal retransfer &mdash; with artwork file format</li>
                </ol>
              </div>

              <div class="rounded-2xl border border-gray-200 bg-gray-50 p-6">
                <p class="eyebrow-label text-[#0d7377] mb-3">Section B &middot; Commercial terms (separates resellers from manufacturers)</p>
                <ol class="space-y-3 text-sm text-gray-700">
                  <li><strong>7. MOQ + price brackets</strong> &mdash; pricing at 1K / 10K / 100K / 1M units. If the vendor only quotes one bracket, they're likely a reseller marking up spot inventory.</li>
                  <li><strong>8. Lead time from PO to shipment</strong> &mdash; sample batch, first production order, repeat orders. Red flag: vague "2-8 weeks" answer.</li>
                  <li><strong>9. Payment terms</strong> &mdash; T/T deposit %, balance trigger (before ship, after delivery, after acceptance), credit terms for repeat buyers</li>
                  <li><strong>10. Incoterm + origin port</strong> &mdash; EXW / FOB / CIF / DDP clearly stated, origin port named. Avoid "FOB China" &mdash; China has 100+ ports.</li>
                  <li><strong>11. Chip supply guarantee</strong> &mdash; are they buying chips on spot market or do they have direct NXP / Impinj / EM supply? This determines reliability during chip shortages.</li>
                </ol>
              </div>

              <div class="rounded-2xl border border-gray-200 bg-gray-50 p-6">
